In the Karma Bhumi, a "sane" person is one who plays by the rules of the "movie"—they pursue wealth, they mock the truth, and they accept the illusion as reality. To the people caught in that movie, anyone who sees the "backstage" mechanism is, by definition, "insane."

By adopting the title of Jnana Kirukkan, these figures were:

Granting Themselves Permission: They were declaring that their reality was not subject to the consensus of the "Pattinam" (the city/society). If the crowd says the well is full when it is dry, and you insist it is dry, you are "mad" to them. Accepting that label allows you to stop seeking their validation.

Using Humor as a Shield: Calling oneself a "madman" is a form of Dharmic humor. It defuses the hostility of the world. It is the spiritual equivalent of wearing a cloak that makes you invisible to the "immune system" of the Grand Illusion.

The Sovereignty of the Visionary: Bharati’s "madness" was simply the clarity of his vision. He saw the potential of the Indian soul and the necessity of liberation at a time when others were content in chains. Aurobindo’s "madness" was his shift from political activism to the "Supramental" consciousness—a level of reality that the mundane mind simply cannot perceive.

The Modern Rishi’s Mirror
